<h1>P8 - User Evaluation & Prototype Revision #2</h1>

<h2>Introduction</h2>
	<p>
		The system serves as a companion to the game Risk Legacy. It simplifies the lengthy rulebook it simple reminders for each player's turn. It also tracks player bonuses and territories so that it can calculate a display a count of how many troops each player gets on their turn.
	</p>
	<p>
		The team conducted basic usability tests by setting up a Risk Legacy board as if it were the beginning of a turn and put the system on one team member’s laptop. Participants were directed through three tasks using the system while the team observed and took notes on any errors. Participants were also interviewed about their opinions on the system. The tests recorded user errors made as well as general user opinion about the system.
	</p>

<h2>Executive Summary</h2>
	<p>
		The project team conducted a usability study for the Risk Legacy project on April 17th, 2016 in Northeastern University's West Village H Lab. The study aimed to identify remaining problems in the system’s prototype.
	</p>
	<p>
		Five participants with varying familiarity of the game Risk Legacy were brought it to participate in 20 minute sessions. They were asked to complete tasks and asked formal interview questions afterwards.
	</p>
	<p>
		These sessions identified several major problems in:
		<ul>
			<li>Adding territories to the system</li>
			<li>Adding players to a game</li>
			<li>The system information being incorrect</li>
		</ul>
	</p>
	<p>
		These sessions identified several major problems in:
		<ul>
			<li>The drop down menus being hard to read</li>
			<li>Poor grouping of some of the elements in the quick view screen</li>
		</ul>
	</p>
	<p>
		This document contains a description of the participants and the session, task results, interview results, and recommendations to improve the system.
	</p>



<h2>Methodology</h2>
	<h3>Sessions</h3>
		<p>
			Participants were friends of the team. The were brought to the West Village H lab where they spent 10-20 minutes completing assigned tasks and answering questions. Prior to testing they were each asked if they had played Risk Legacy before and if not if they were familiar with any Risk game.
		</p>
		<p>
			After completing the tasks they were asked the following questions:
			<ul>
				<li>Did you find this system useful?</li>
				<li>What was your least favorite part of the system?</li>
				<li>If you could change one thing about this system what would you change to make it more useful or easier to use.</li>
			</ul>
		</p>
	<h3>Participants</h3>
		<p>
			Participants were Northeastern University students. Five participants were gathered to run tests on April 17th. All had at least some familiarity with the game Risk but only two had played Risk Legacy before. No other demographic information was collected.
		</p>
	<h3>Evaluation Tasks/Scenarios</h3>
		<p>
			Participants were asked to complete the following tasks:
			<ul>
				<li>Start a game with 5 players.</li>
				<li>Enter conquered territories and end their turn.</li>
				<li>Find what player was in the faction Enclave of the Bear.</li>
			</ul>
		</p>

