	<h3>Summary Of Data</h3>

		<p>
			The average error data showed that participants struggled the most with the first task, starting a game with five players. Based on observation and interview question responses these problems are caused by confusion around how to enter territories and add players. Multiple participants had trouble adding a territory to a player. This was mainly caused by participants typing a full territory name into the field rather than relying on the dropdown menu. This was most likely because they had to map in front of them to reference territory names, or were familiar enough with Risk to know.
		</p>
		<p>
			The second common problem was adding the final player. Multiple participants noted that it was strange to have to click add player to get the new bar to appear and then click it again to add the new player.
		</p>

		<p>
			The only problem from Task 2 is really a repeat of the problem that participants had adding territories when adding players. The same dropdown feature is used in both places.
		</p>
		<p>
			The only problem from Task 3 is an outlier and more of a problem with a participant doing something that wouldn’t happen in an actual game. He wouldn’t skip over multiple turns to find out what faction a certain player was.
		</p>

		<p>
			The interview answers were varied. Overall the responses to the first question are divided between the two participants who are familiar with Risk Legacy and the two who aren’t. The newer players felt that the system was helpful and saw more potential for it, where the two who had played Risk Legacy a lot before were more critical. 
		</p>
		<p>
			Questions 2 and 3 were about problems and possible changes to the system. The most common responses were add a background to the dropdown, and change the add player interface.
		</p>


